n=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ...</span><hr size=1> Only two generalizations I'd make about 'ubers' (I've known/met quite a good number):<br>
<br>
1. Tend to be grossly out of shape/unhealthy. Either too overweight, too skinny, no muscle tone, bad posture, etc.<br>
<br>
2. Most of them do not have a spouse and kids (%ubers v. %casual not even close).<br>
<br>
Again - these are just generalizations.  They tend to be very normal/average people with different backgrounds and situations.<br>
<br>
Vokal <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#3B3B3B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/usilvaneq.showPublicProfile?language=EN>SilvanEQ</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(2/13/02 7:00:29 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehouseloungegeneraldiscussion.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=22089.topic&index=178>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ...</span><hr size=1> Saw a few responses to what I said a week or so ago. I really like this thread. I should clarify what I suggested in my previous post:<br>
<br>
I dont think that a guild who plays less should get equal access. The idea behind my suggestion of random timing of mobs after server downtime was to make it so casual guilds had a shot at having a mob up when they have a sufficient force to take them.<br>
There were responses that talked about the lack of expertise and skill at assembling a crew by the casual guild. At least on my server the casual guilds usually have people who have the skills to have a shot at it. The point of the original post was that many casual guilds are getting to the point where they CAN take down these mobs, its what is left in the game for them but have severely diminished opportunity.<br>
The problem is that the casual gamer guilds are restricted to specific time slots where they can assemble a crew. These time slots usually do not match up with the weekday/midday patch times.<br>
Random spawn delays/locations would create a situation where the casual guild at least had a chance of a mob spawning during their regular play times that they take a shot at when they are in force. The random location would perhaps prevent the 'camping' of a mob long before it spawned. Perhaps it wouldnt but it would be hard to reserve a mob when you dont know where he is going to spawn. <br>
Most casual guilds have raid times where they all get together and their numbers double or triple, if a mob spawned during these times they could potentially set up and defeat it just like any other guild if they have the skills. Not an equal chance but at least a chance for a uber mob to be up at the times when they play. It doesnt take away from the fact that the professional guilds will have a better shot at the mob (which they should) but rather makes it so it isnt a 100% monopoly based around the patch times. Some mobs are already like this and now it looks like more of them will be with todays patch message.<br>
<br>
From todays patch message:<br>
&quot;Many higher level NPCs now have a random delay before they initially spawn. This means that they will appear at a more random time interval after servers or zones are brought up. This is designed to provide a fairer distribution of these NPCs across all time zones&quot;<br>
<br>
The second suggestion which some people liked was the quests for items which can spawn uber mobs. This one is particularly best for the casual gamers. Its not that any of us are asking for the right to spend less time to get something, rather that we are asking for the ability to spend the same time and get the same reward. Our time is broken into smaller sessions over longer intervals. The game design is currently catoring to quick hits for the biggest rewards. It looks to me with many of the triggered Luclin quests they got the right idea.<br>
<br>
The last suggestion was to create more areas like the &quot;Kael Arena&quot; where there were a large number of mobs which had a small chance of dropping an piece for a quest for a high end item. Looks to me like that does exist in Luclin and its far more complex than the Velious version. So much of what I suggested is already being implemented and im certain was not new ideas.<br>
<br>
So if you actually read my long post it really comes down to one argument.<br>
<br>
If you play the game you should be rewarded according to how much time &amp; skill you put into it. The rewards should not be limited to people who can play at specific times or for specific intervals. If the rewards require a large force to obtain there needs to be some way of giving those who have these types of forces together less frequently a shot at the same rewards all be it a smaller one.<br>
<br>
Thanks for reading... Time to stop wasting work time and get home and play EQ.<br>
<br>
